.SH "NAME"
atalkd.conf \- Configuration file used by \fBatalkd\fR(8) to configure the interfaces used by AppleTalk
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.PP
\fBatalkd\&.conf\fR
is the configuration file used by atalkd to configure the Appletalk interfaces and their behavior
.PP
Any line not prefixed with
\fB#\fR
is interpreted\&. Each interface has be configured on an uninterrupted line, with no support for split lines\&. The configuration line format is:
.PP
\fIinterface\fR
[
\fB\-seed\fR
] [
\fB\-phase\fR
\fInumber\fR
] [
\fB\-net\fR
\fInet\-range\fR
] [
\fB\-addr\fR
\fIaddress\fR
] [
\fB\-zone\fR
\fIzonename\fR
] \&.\&.\&.
.PP
The simplest case is to have either no atalkd\&.conf, or to have one that has no active lines\&. In this case, atalkd will auto\-discover the local interfaces on the machine and write to the atalkd\&.conf file, creating it if one does not exist\&.
.PP
The interface is the network interface that this to work over, such as
\fBeth0\fR
for Linux, or
\fBle0\fR
for Solaris\&.
.PP
Note that all fields except the interface are optional\&. The loopback interface is configured automatically\&. If
\fB\-seed\fR
is specified, all other fields must be present\&. Also,
\fBatalkd\fR
will exit during startup if a router disagrees with its seed information\&. If
\fB\-seed\fR
is not given, all other information may be overridden during auto\-configuration\&. If no
\fB\-phase\fR
option is given, the default phase as given on the command line is used (the default is 2)\&. If
\fB\-addr\fR
is given and
\fB\-net\fR
is not, a net\-range of one is assumed\&.
.PP
The first \-zone directive for each interface is the ``default\*(Aq\*(Aq zone\&. Under Phase 1, there is only one zone\&. Under Phase 2, all routers on the network are configured with the default zone and must agree\&.
\fBatalkd\fR
maps ``*\*(Aq\*(Aq to the default zone of the first interface\&. Note: The default zone for a machine is determined by the configuration of the local routers; to appear in a non\-default zone, each service, e\&.g\&.
\fBafpd\fR, must individually specify the desired zone\&. See also
\fBnbp_name\fR(3)\&.
.PP
The possible options and their meanings are:
.PP
\fB\-addr \fR\fB\fInet\&.node\fR\fR
.RS 4
Allows specification of the net and node numbers for this interface, specified in AppleTalk numbering format (example:
\fB\-addr 66\&.6\fR)\&.
.RE
.PP
\fB\-dontroute\fR
.RS 4
Disables AppleTalk routing\&. It is the inverse of
\fB\-router\fR\&.
.RE
.PP
\fB\-net first[\-last]\fR
.RS 4
Allows the available net to be set, optionally as a range\&.
.RE
.PP
\fB\-phase ( 1 | 2 )\fR
.RS 4
Specifies the AppleTalk phase that this interface is to use (either Phase 1 or Phase 2)\&.
.RE
.PP
\fB\-router\fR
.RS 4
Seed an AppleTalk router on a single interface\&. The inverse option is
\fB\-dontroute\fR\&. Akin to
\fB\-seed\fR, but allows single interface routing\&.
.RE
.PP
\fB\-seed\fR
.RS 4
Seed an AppleTalk router\&. This requires two or more interfaces to be configured\&. If you have a single network interface, use
\fB\-route\fR
instead\&. It also causes all missing arguments to be automagically configured from the network\&.
.RE
.PP
\fB\-zone \fR\fB\fIzonename\fR\fR
.RS 4
Specifies a specific zone that this interface should appear on (example:
\fB\-zone "Parking Lot"\fR)\&. Please note that zones with spaces and other special characters should be enclosed in parentheses\&.
.RE
.SH "EXAMPLES"
.PP
Single interface on Solaris with auto\-detected parameters\&.
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
   le0
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.PP
The same on Linux\&.
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
   eth0
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.PP
Below is an example configuration file from a Sun 4/40\&. The machine has two interfaces, ``le0\*(Aq\*(Aq and ``le1\*(Aq\*(Aq\&. The ``le0\*(Aq\*(Aq interface is configured automatically from other routers on the network\&. The machine is the only router for the ``le1\*(Aq\*(Aq interface\&.
.PP
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
   le0
   le1 \-seed \-net 9461\-9471 \-zone netatalk \-zone Argus
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
